==Affiliated businesses==
From its inception, Apollo built as part of a network of affiliated businesses focusing on [[private equity]] and a variety of [[distressed securities|distressed]] investment strategies.  

===Lion Advisors===
Lion Advisors (or Lion Capital), which was founded at the same time as Apollo in 1990, focused on investment management and consulting services to foreign institutional accounts targeting investments in public and private high yield debt securities in the US.  In 1992, Lion entered into a more formal arrangement to manage the $3 billion high-yield portfolio for Credit Lyonnais which together with a consortium of other international investors provided the capital for Lion's investment activities.  The Lion business would ultimately be replaced by Ares Management.<ref name=aresprospectus>[http://www.financialregulator.ie/data/in_mark_prosp/10270%20Prospectus.pdf Ares Enhanced Loan Investment Strategy IR, Ltd. Prospectus]. September 22, 2008</ref>

===Ares Management===
{{Infobox_Company 
|  company_name   = 
|  company_logo   = [[Image: Ares Management logo.png|130px|ARES Management logo]]
|  company_type   = [[Private company|Private]]
|  foundation     = 1997, 2002 (independent)
|  homepage       = [http://www.aresmgmt.com www.aresmgmt.com] 
}}
Ares Management, founded in 1997, was established initially was formed to manage a $1.2 billion [[Collateralized debt obligation#Structures|market value collateralized debt obligation vehicle]].  Ares would grow to manage a family of [[collateralized loan obligation]] (CLO) vehicles that would invest in capital markets-based securities including senior bank loans and high-yield and mezzanine debt.  Ares was founded by Anthony Ressler and John H. Kissick, both partners at Apollo as well as Bennett Rosenthal, who joined the group from the global leveraged finance group at [[Merrill Lynch]].<ref name=newfundpublic>[http://articles.latimes.com/2004/apr/22/business/fi-ares22 Ares Management to Take New Fund Public].  Los Angeles Times, April 22, 2004</ref>

Ares I and II which were raised were structured as [[Collateralized debt obligation#Structures|market value CLOs]].  Ares III though Ares X  were structured as [[Collateralized debt obligation#Structures|cash flow CLOs]].  In 2002, Ares completed a spinout from Apollo management.  Although technically, the founders of Ares had completed a spinout with the formation of the firm in 1997, they had maintained a close relationship with Apollo over its first five years and operated as the West Coast affiliate of Apollo.   Shortly thereafter, Ares completed fundraising for Ares Corporate Opportunities Fund, a special situations investment fund with $750 million of capital under management.<ref name=newfundpublic /><ref name=aresprospectus />

In 2004, Ares debuted a publicly traded [[business development company]], Ares Capital Corporation ([http://finance.yahoo.com/q?s=ARCC NYSE:ARCC]).<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/06/business/fi-wrap6.2 Ares Capital IPO Raises $165 Million].  Los Angeles Times, October 06, 2004</ref>  In 2006, Ares raised a $2.1 billion successor special situations fund (Ares Corporate Opportunities Fund II).<ref name=newfundpublic />

===AREA Property Partners (Apollo Real Estate Advisors)===
{{Infobox_Company 
|  company_name   = 
|  company_logo   = [[Image: AREA Property Partners logo.png|200px|AREA Property Partners  logo]]
|  company_type   = [[Private company|Private]]
|  foundation     = 1993
|  homepage       = [http://www.areapropertypartners.com www.areapropertypartners.com] 
}}
AREA Property Partners, originally Apollo Real Estate, was founded in 1993 by William Mack, to take advantage of opportunities to purchase distressed properties as many real estate markets crashed in the early 1990s.<ref>[http://www.wharton.upenn.edu/alum_mag/issues/125anniversaryissue/mack.html He Made Real Estate a Science: William L. Mack, W<U+2019>61].  Wharton School of Business Alumni Magazine, Spring 2007</ref>  

Apollo Real Estate Investment Fund, L.P., the first in a family of real estate <U+201C>opportunity funds<U+201D> was closed in April 1993 with $500 million of investor commitments.  As of 2008, the firm was investing out of three funds: Apollo Real Estate Investment Fund V, Apollo European Real Estate Fund II and Apollo Value Enhancement Fund VII. In 2004, Apollo Real Estate acquired the Value Enhancement Funds family of investment vehicles to broaden its offerings in the <U+201C>value-added<U+201D> segment of the real estate investment spectrum. Apollo also operates a real estate mezzanine lending program.<ref>[http://www.hedgeweek.com/articles/detail.jsp?content_id=259781 Apollo Real Estate Advisors closes Apollo Value Enhancement Fund VII with USD758m].  Hedge Week, July 8, 2008</ref>

